Înainte de documentație, o observație de design: cred că aceste două mecanisme completează foarte frumos Semantic Schemas. Unul este composition by inclusion (flatten), celălalt este composition by nesting (ierarhic). Nu introduc tipuri noi și păstrează filosofia actuală a LogTScript.

───

Schema composition (merge and nested schemas)
Semantic Schemas may be composed from other schemas. LogTScript supports two composition forms:
• Schema merge (<schema>) – copy all fields from another schema into the current one.
• Nested schema (field:<schema>) – embed another schema as a named field.
Neither form changes the underlying wire layout. Both are compile-time descriptions only.

───

Schema merge
Place another schema on its own line inside a schema definition.
logts
<flags>:
    carry:1
    zero:1
    negative:1
    overflow:1
:

<instruction>:
    opcode:4
    <flags>
    immediate:8
:

Equivalent to:
logts
<instruction>:
    opcode:4
    carry:1
    zero:1
    negative:1
    overflow:1
    immediate:8
:

The merged schema is expanded at compile time. Field offsets are computed exactly as if the fields had been written directly.

───

Nested schemas
A schema may also appear as the type of a named field.
logts
<flags>:
    carry:1
    zero:1
    negative:1
    overflow:1
:

<instruction>:
    opcode:4
    flags:<flags>
    immediate:8
:

Unlike schema merge, the nested schema remains grouped under its field name.
Access:
logts
instr:flags:carry
instr:flags:zero
instr:flags:overflow

instead of
logts
instr:carry
instr:zero


───

Merge vs nested

Syntax
Behaviour

<schema>
Merge all fields into the current schema (flatten).

field:<schema>
Create a nested semantic object accessible through field:.


Example:
logts
<header>:
    version:4
    type:4
:

<packet>:
    <header>
    payload:8
:

becomes
text
version
type
payload

while
logts
<packet>:
    header:<header>
    payload:8
:

becomes
text
header
    version
    type

payload


───

Nested schemas may be nested again
Schemas may contain any number of nested schemas.
logts
<rgb>:
    r:8
    g:8
    b:8
:

<pixel>:
    color:<rgb>
    alpha:8
:

Access:
logts
pixel:color:r
pixel:color:g
pixel:color:b
pixel:alpha


───

Combining both forms
Both composition mechanisms may appear in the same schema.
logts
<header>:
    version:4
    type:4
:

<flags>:
    carry:1
    zero:1
:

<packet>:
    <header>
    flags:<flags>
    crc:16
:

Result:
text
version
type

flags
    carry
    zero

crc

The header fields are merged into the packet, while flags remains a nested semantic object.

───

Bit layout
Composition never inserts padding.
Field offsets are assigned sequentially in declaration order, whether fields originate from the current schema or from merged schemas.
Nested schemas occupy exactly the sum of their contained field widths.
Example:
logts
<sub>:
    a:3
    b:5
:

<test>:
    x:4
    child:<sub>
    y:4
:

Bit layout:
text
x       4 bits
child
    a   3 bits
    b   5 bits
y       4 bits

Total width:
4 + (3 + 5) + 4 = 16 bits


───

show()
When a wire has an associated semantic schema, show() displays nested schemas hierarchically.
logts
16wire<instruction> instr
show(instr)

Output:
text
instr

opcode = ADD

flags
    carry = 1
    zero = 0
    overflow = 0

immediate = 15

Merged schemas appear as normal top-level fields.

───

Rules
• <schema> merges all fields from another schema into the current schema.
• field:<schema> embeds another schema under a field name.
• Both operations are compile-time only.
• Neither changes the stored wire value.
• Field offsets remain deterministic and follow declaration order.
• Nested schemas may themselves contain merged or nested schemas recursively.
